{"key":"processedPost-11068825","value":{"id":11068825,"first":11068790,"last":11068840,"when":1253113000,"utime":"09/16/09 05:56 PM","cleanedPost":"The idea behind cooling in the pan you cooked them in is that they cool slower.&nbsp; As the contents of a jar cool, they contract, drawing in air from outside the jar.&nbsp; If you took steaming hot jars out of the pressure cooker or boiling kettle, the rapid cooldown could easily overwhelm your filters, causing air to be drawn in around or under the filter, rather than through it.<br />You can use synthetic filter disks thousands of times.&nbsp; Tyvek works a 'few' times before it tears where the jar lid cuts into it at the lid/glass interface.&nbsp; Synthetic filter disks are the way to go if you're using jars.<br />RR"}}